Contrary to many countries where development is often associated with investments in cities and other urban centres, China prioritised rural areas in its poverty reduction efforts where agriculture played a major role.       

China’s efforts offer good insights for Kenya’s socio-economic transformation. Since 1949 when the Republic was founded, China’s agriculture has undergone a series of improvements spanning land reforms and agricultural cooperatives. 

Hoisted by modern farming methods, targeted institutions as well as progressive policies, the shift from subsistence to comprehensive agricultural production, economically empowered China’s rural majority, and formed a key component of its poverty reduction feat.     



